datasetName: Pacific Marine Life Survey Dive Records
identificationRemarks: Two subspecies are recognized: a Californian subspecies, Apata pricei pricei, as originally described from Monterey, California, and a Western Pacific subspecies, Apata pricei komandorica. No specimens have been sequenced to determine which subspecies are present in the Salish Sea. However, we do not appear to have the subspecies originally described in MacFarland 1966.

scientificNameAuthorship: Korshunova, Fletcher, Picton, Lundin, Kashio, N. Sanamyan, K. Sanamyan, Padula, Schrödl & Martynov, 2020
georeferenceProtocol: interpretation of locality, and/or inference based on local knowledge and species ecology
georeferenceRemarks: shunted to adjacent waters in Retreat Cove
identificationRemarks: Currently, there is a sequence of Cadlina klasmalmbergi from Galiano Island in GenBank, but none of the other species that make up this complex—Cadlina jannanicholsae, Cadlina sylviaearleae or Cadlina luteomarginata—are yet represented. Two of the three other species have been sequenced from BC—C. jannanicholsae and C. luteomarginata. The latter has been sequenced from Alaska and Washington and is therefore likely present in BC. Without more focused collecting and genetic study, however, one cannot be certain of the local diversity.

scientificNameAuthorship: Korshunova, Fletcher, Picton, Lundin, Kashio, N. Sanamyan, K. Sanamyan, Padula, Schrödl & Martynov, 2020

identificationRemarks: Currently, there is a sequence of Cadlina klasmalmbergi from Galiano Island in GenBank, but none of the other species that make up this complex—Cadlina jannanicholsae, Cadlina sylviaearleae or Cadlina luteomarginata—are yet represented. Two of the three other species have been sequenced from BC—C. jannanicholsae and C. luteomarginata. The latter has been sequenced from Alaska and Washington and is therefore likely present in BC. Without more focused collecting and genetic study, however, one cannot be certain of the local diversity.

datasetName: Pacific Marine Life Survey Dive Records
identificationRemarks: PMLS records list Cadlina luteomarginata complex due to challenges in field identification. However, here we recognize both Cadlina klasmalmbergi and Cadlina luteomarginata based on other confirmed observations. True Cadlina luteomarginata have more conspicuous tubercles and lack yellow glands near the mantle edge. Cadlina klasmalmbergi is more common in BC than C. luteomarginata.

True Cadlina luteomarginata have more conspicuous tubercles and lack yellow glands near the mantle edge. Cadlina klasmalmbergi is more common in BC than C. luteomarginata.
